[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **FDA IND/IDE record-retention floor for FDA-regulated trials.** Where the trial is FDA-regulated, the recruitment material is part of the IND or IDE record. The IND/IDE record-retention floor (typically two years after a marketing application is approved or, where no application is approved or filed, two years after the investigation is discontinued and the FDA is notified, with longer obligations in many cases) often exceeds general medical-record retention. <!-- Reviewer's hedge: 21 CFR Part 312 IND record retention provisions and 21 CFR Part 812 IDE record retention provisions establish specific floors; trial-specific obligations may extend further. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **State-specific clinical-trial recruitment regulations.** Some states have specific provisions on clinical-trial recruitment material, on clinical-research informed-consent supplements, and on patient-advertising-as-regulated-communication. The architecture should specify per-state regulatory configuration with legal-counsel review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **Information Blocking rule and 21st Century Cures Act audit-trail obligations.** Where the recruitment workflow surfaces clinical data (an EHR-integrated prescreen path or a patient's prior lab values shared as eligibility-criterion verification), the Information Blocking rule audit-trail obligations apply. The architecture should specify per-recruitment-data-flow audit-trail compliance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   6. **Patient right-of-access and (per state and per institutional policy) right-of-deletion workflow.** Patients have a HIPAA right-of-access to their recruitment-conversation records where the records are part of the institution's designated record set. Per state and per institutional policy, the right-of-deletion may apply to records that are not subject to FDA IND/IDE retention or to litigation-hold or to other regulatory floors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   7. **Patient-data-purge-on-decline workflow.** Where a prospective participant declines to participate, the institutional research-data policy may require a different retention disposition than where the prospective participant is screen-failed or where the prospective participant is qualified-and-handed-off. The architecture should specify the per-disposition retention path.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   8. **Multi-trial isolation across the working stores.** A patient may be a candidate for multiple trials in a therapeutic area, and the prose elevates the multi-trial scenario explicitly. The architecture should specify the per-trial-isolated working-store partitioning so that a patient's interaction with Trial A's recruitment conversationalist does not leak into Trial B's working store except where the institutional research-recruitment infrastructure has explicit cross-trial-coordination provisions.
